default4. defaultEmissionsdefaultMany solid mineral fuels are authorised for use in smoke control areas. This is because they are very low in 
defaultmoisture and 
defaultvolatile organic content (less than 10% 
defaultvolatiles 
defaultcompared to around 
default50-
default60% for wood fuel)
default. Smokeless mineral fuels
default 
defaultburn very cleanly 
defaultwith low levels of organic gaseous and particulate emissions. 
defaultWith regard to 
defaultgreenhouse gas 
defaultemissions, 
defaultit is an indisputable fact that when anything burns, carbon dioxide is emitted. However, 
defaultthe SFA believe that an artificial distinction is 
defaultbeing 
defaultmade be
defaulttween coal and other 
defaultcompeting 
defaultfuels. For instance, woody biomass is assumed to be carbon neutral when in fact this is only partially true even for wood from a sustainable source. 
defaultAny type of fuel requires the input of energy to bring it to the market – me
defaultchanical harvesting, transport and preparation/processing must be taken into account to arrive at an energy return against
default energy
default invest
defaulted
default. This is sometimes expressed as an EPR (Energy Performance Ratio). An EPR of less than 1 indicates that more energy h
defaultas been invested than returned. 
defaultFor timber 
defaultobtained 
defaultfrom non-sustainable sources, the carbon dioxide emissions are at least as great as for coal. For a highly processed 
defaultand imported 
defaultproduct such as wood pellets, the
default CO₂
default emissions 
defaultare likely to
default 
defaultbe greater 
defaultthan for coal.
defaultIn reality, the total indigenous supply of sustainable wood fuel is 
defaultextremely limited and when added to the growing demand from electricity generators, 80% of wood fuel 
defaultwill be imported in bulk carriers from overseas. In many cases, this imp
defaultorted timber is produced by the clear felling of thousands of acres of virgin forest which is not replanted. This not only has a catastrophic effect on local ecosystems but also means that this material is by no means renewable. Even if trees were replante
defaultd, it would take many decades or even centuries to re-sequester the amount of carbon dioxide emitted during combustion. This is known as a “carbon debt”. Because biomass emits more carbon dioxide than 
defaultmineral fuel
default per kW of 
defaultheat energy
default generated, emissions
default over any sensible timescale are greater than for coal.
defaultTo make matters worse, the pellets themselves are a highly processed product requiring high levels of energy input throughout their production and transport.
defaultWe understand that t
defaulthe Government’s own an
defaultalysis shows that the use of whole trees as power station feedstock will increase greenhouse gas emissions by at least 49% compared to coal (Searchinger 2012). 
defaultPower station use is likely to completely eclipse the domestic supply chain and eliminate
default even
default t
defaulthe 
defaultvery 
defaultdubious environmental benefits of biomass.
defaultIt should be obvious to all, regardless of political affiliation or views on climate change that measures aimed at limiting greenhouse gas emissions should not increase them. 
defaultAs far as wood fuel is concerned, the SFA firmly believe that the very limited supplies of indigenous wood fuel would be better burnt 
defaultalongside mineral fuel 
defaulton domestic stoves at 70% efficiency rather than in power stations at 30% efficiency.
default&#xa0;
defaultA 
default2012
default report by 
defaultPrincet
defaulton academic Timothy Searchinger entitled “Dirtier than coal?”suggests that emissions from biomass are 49% greater than for coal.
defaultLocally sourced
default,
default well-seasoned logs will have the 
defaultlowest emissions among biomass products. 
defaultIndeed, a
default multifue
defaultl stove burning a 50:50 mix of coal and logs from a sustainable 
defaultwoodland 
defaultsource could have a smaller “carbon footprint” than a gas boiler.
defaultIf we compare coal
default 
defaultto 
defaultnatural gas
default,
default carbon dioxide emissions 
defaultfor gas 
defaultat the point of use are lower than for coal, givi
defaultng 
defaultit
default a lower 
default“
defaultcarbon intensity
default”
default. However,
default the total 
default“
defaultglobal warming potential
default”
default of gas may be very much greater than 
defaultthis
default figure
default indicates
default due to
default unintentional releases, 
defaultleakage
defaults
default from pipelines etc. 
defaultThis is because 
defaultmethane
default (natural gas)
default is considered to have a global 
defaultwarming potential 
default23
default times 
defaultgreater than carbon dioxide.
default 
defaultShale gas has been widely touted 
defaultin
default some quarters as a “silver bullet” for energy supplies. Unfortunately, despite the hype, shale gas has one massive problem-the gree
defaultnhouse gas emissions and environmental damage are likely to be far greater than for coal.
default 
defaultAccording to a recent study (European Commission 1 September 2011), 
defaultthe greenhouse gas footprint of shale gas is greater than that of 
defaultboth 
defaultcoal
default and
default oil.
defaultLosses of 
defaultmethane occur during the development of the wells, the extraction process and during the transport, storage and distribution of the gas.
defaultOverall, the life cycle estimated losses of methane emissions from a typical shale gas well amount to 3.6 to 7.9 per ce
defaultnt of the total amount of gas produced by the well. This compares with methane losses of 1.7 to 6 per cent of total gas production from conventional wells.
defaultAs we have already seen, accepted 
defaultclimate
default theory has it that methane
default’s
default global warming potential 
defaultis 
default2
default3 times as great as carbon dioxide. Therefore, the greenhouse gas footprint of shale gas production-primarily due to these uncontrollable methane emissions- could be up to twice the footprint for coal (data based on a European Commission report 1 September
default 2011).
defaultOther drawbacks for shale gas include the risk of groundwater contamination by the fracturing fluids, risk of earthquakes beneath residential areas and also the sheer number of wells that would be necessary to maintain 
defaulta reasonable level of 
defaultproduct
defaultion 
defaultbecause of the short-lived l
defaultifespan of each individual well. T
defaulthis could be as many as 10,000 wells across the UK
default (estimated by 
defaultBloomberg New Energy Finance
default)
default. 
defaultIn summary, if climate change theory is accepted, the substitution of gas for coal as an energy source results in increased rather than decreased global warming.
defaultIf the security of natural gas supplies depends on the rapid development of a UK shale gas ind
defaultustry, then even the very dubious
default 
defaultenvironmental advantage of conventional gas over coal is completely lost. 
defaultOne could easily argue that if global warming can be safely ignored in the case of shale gas, why not in the case of coal?
defaultMoreover, if we are able
default to ignore risks from global warming, why try to reduce coal’s contribution to the UK energy
default and heating
default mix in the first place?
defaultThe SFA fully supports 
defaultthe drive
default to exploit new sources of fossil fuels. However, it needs to be emphasized strongly that repla
defaultcement of coal with shale gas has no environmental justification.
